				</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-411006">
		<article id="comment-411006" class="comment">
			<footer>
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
										<cite class="fn">Mark Hamilton</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>				</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
				
				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
					<a href="https://nautilus.org/napsnet/napsnet-special-reports/mind-the-gap-between-rhetoric-and-reality/#comment-411006"><time pubdate datetime="2017-10-01T18:13:19-07:00">
					October 1, 2017 at 6:13 pm					</time></a>
										</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>Perhaps those deeply immersed in the lingo of strategic analysis find this to be a &#8220;magnificent piece&#8221; but found it&#8217;s value to the lay public undermined by poor organization, poor proof-reading, and frequently opaque and shifting meanings.</p>
<p>I had hoped for clear summations in figures and tables, instead I found confusing shifts in Scenario &#8220;names&#8221; and inappropriate comparative data. </p>
<p>After some head scratching over shifting scenario names in different tables, I now assume that four of the named scenarios (depending on which table one reads) are really two? A and C are the same, B and D are the same, correct?</p>
<p>a) &#8220;Surprise Volley (Primarily counter-force)<br />
b) &#8220;Surprise Volley (Countervalue and a-strategic)<br />
c) &#8220;KPA primarily counter-force&#8221;<br />
d) &#8220;KPA counter-value Likely indicates KPA desperation&#8221;</p>
<p>If so, it would be most useful to actually use the SAME and COMPLETE data for each scenario. For example, &#8220;c&#8221; lists both first volley, first day, and week end casualties, but &#8220;d&#8221; lists ONLY first volley casualties BUT nothing on first day or week end casualties. </p>
<p>Then the report says: &#8220;Here’s an analytical look at the numbers in two scenarios:</p>
<p>&#8211; KPA relatively close to doctrine conventional artillery attack, mainly counter-force<br />
&#8211; KPA conventional artillery attack mainly counter-force.&#8221;</p>
<p>The same Scenario with titles that sound almost identical. Is this right or is it an error in proof reading? If is right how does it track to the tables? </p>
<p>Another part states&#8221;However, if we make one assumption change, that most people are either at home or an office, in other words most people are NOT outside standing in the open, then the casualties, while still horrendous, change drastically to a projected 252,000 fatalities in an initial barrage.&#8221;</p>
<p>That can&#8217;t be right &#8211; another proof-reading error? </p>
<p>And under the subheading of &#8220;Major (and) Secondary Factors&#8221; it says &#8220;these results are summarized in Figure 1.&#8221; I went to Figure 1 for &#8220;these results&#8221; and it was a map with indecipherable overlays of overlapped lines, then overlaid with blue colored smudges, &#8220;summarizing&#8221; almost nothing about the data presented (e.g. dud rates, shelter protection, actual numbers, etc.). I expected a table.</p>
<p>I could add more, but you get the point. IF you wish to present a summary (which is always a good idea) you need to answer the same questions for all possible scenarios. In short:</p>
<p>DEFINE the scenario and terms and use identical naming conventions.<br />
DEFINE the meaning of casualties (dead and wounded or just dead?).<br />
DEFINE the geographic scope of casualties (e.g. are all counter-force casualties for the entire front or just the Seoul metroplex?<br />
USE the same criteria for comparison. </p>
<p>After all, I was trying to figure out the number of dead, wounded, in SK as a whole, as well as just in Seoul over &#8220;one volley&#8221;.</p>
<p>Thanks<br />
Mark Hamilton</p>
</div>

			<div class="reply">
					<a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='https://nautilus.org/napsnet/napsnet-special-reports/mind-the-gap-between-rhetoric-and-reality/?replytocom=411006#respond' data-commentid="411006" data-postid="24982" data-belowelement="comment-411006" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Mark Hamilton" aria-label='Reply to Mark Hamilton'>Reply</a>			</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->

				</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-411086">
		<article id="comment-411086" class="comment">
			<footer>
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
										<cite class="fn">Thompson jones</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>				</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
				
				<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
					<a href="https://nautilus.org/napsnet/napsnet-special-reports/mind-the-gap-between-rhetoric-and-reality/#comment-411086"><time pubdate datetime="2017-11-02T21:32:38-07:00">
					November 2, 2017 at 9:32 pm					</time></a>
										</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->
			</footer>

			<div class="comment-content"><p>This Study seems to have alot of flaws firstly the 240mm MRL&#8217;s have a range of around 60km which can hit most of Seoul.<br />
Secondly this study doesn&#8217;t account for and ignores chemical munitions which are thought to be pre-deployed on some of these systems.</p>
<p>Thirdly this study assumes that kpa would move There artillery away from the safety of the HARTS which would make them extremely vulnerable to enemy attacks also kpa has other systems to accomplish this goal.</p>
<p>Fourthly while I do agree that we should expect and there could be duds the 25% dud rate seems to be based off the BM-21 mrl from the shelling of yeonpyeong island which is a completely different system I&#8217;m mentioning this because dud rates differentiate from system to system. </p>
<p>But I&#8217;m writing this comment to say that expected casualties and fatalities could certainly be far higher than what&#8217;s estimated here and to address the numerous other things that weren&#8217;t taken into account 300mm and I do know that all 700 aren&#8217;t actually deployed.</p>
</div>

